BRIEFLY: OTHER NEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gasoline Prices Head Upward: The retail price rose 1 1/2 cents a gallon during 
the past two weeks, reversing a trend of falling prices that began in late 
August, according to a newsletter.The average pump price on Friday was $1.22 a 
gallon, up 1.53 cents from Oct. 21, said Trilby Lundberg, whose publication 
conducts a survey of 10,000 gas stations nationwide. The primary reason for the 
increase was the federally mandated sale of more costly oxygenated gasoline, 
Lundberg said. Prices can be expected to rise again with the Jan. 1 
implementation of federal requirements to sell reformulated gas. 
</P>
