<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; COUNTY PLANNERS OFFER 3RD PLAN FOR 
WETLANDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The county Planning Commission has come up with a third option for the 
development of the Bolsa Chica Wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest option includes a tidal inlet and allows 100 additional homes, 
according to Ron Tippets, county chief of coastal planning. 
</P>
<P>
 Commissioners sought another plan because public comments persuaded them that 
one more option should be considered, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 The third option also includes reducing the acreage of a community park in the 
lowlands and allowing a kayak and canoe facility, Tippets said. 
</P>
<P>
 He added that the facility would allow limited excursions into the wetlands 
for scientific and educational purposes and would be controlled by county park 
rangers and the state Department of Fish and Game. 
</P>
<P>
 Public comments on the third option will be accepted during the next six 
weeks, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Julie Osugi, city associate planner, said the comment period should be 
extended. 
</P>
<P>
 By the time "we turn in comments at the end of the six-week period, based on 
the county's schedule, the county Planning Commission hearings (which conclude 
on Nov. 30) will (have been) completed already. The comments won't get the 
level of review by the Planning Commission as the first set of comments did," 
Osugi said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Koll Real Estate Group proposes to build 4,286 homes, but the county has 
presented options for either 3,200 homes or 2,500 homes. Under the third county 
option, up to 3,300 homes may be built, Tippets said. 
</P>
<P>
 Koll's plan also includes a $20-million tidal inlet to link the wetlands and 
the ocean, and restoration of 1,100 acres of wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
 Chuck Nelson, Amigos de Bolsa Chica president, said: "Without the tidal inlet 
alternative, you're not providing the best alternative for the highest quality 
restoration." 
</P>
<P>
 Gordon LaBedz, a spokesman for Surfrider Foundation, which opposes a tidal 
inlet, said: "In our view, this is a $20-million boondoggle that will flood the 
wetlands and pollute the ocean. . . . It has the potential to erode the beach 
and cliffs." DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
